<p>So, let‚Äôs have a look at how GraphQL is working to solve some of the issues with REST.</p>

<p><em>Note: My examples are written in Ruby/Rails</em></p>

<hr />

<h2 id="a-lot-of-endpoints">A lot of endpoints</h2>
<p>In a REST API, each resource is represented by an endpoint. So, in a real-world application, we could end up having a lot of endpoints for lots of resources. If you want to make a GET request, you would need an endpoint specific to that request, with specific parameters. If you want to make a POST request, you would need another endpoint just for that request.</p>

<p><em>What‚Äôs the problem with that?</em> I hear you ask. Well, let‚Äôs imagine we are building a huge social media application like Facebook. We would potentially end up with a lot of endpoints which means more developer time is going to be spent developing, maintaining and documenting these APIs.</p>

<h2 id="over-and-under-fetching-of-data">Over and under fetching of data</h2>
<p>Because a REST API always returns a fixed structure, we as developers can‚Äôt get exactly the data that we want unless we create a specific endpoint for that data.</p>

<p>We are left with two potential pain points - over and under fetching of data.</p>

<p>So, if we need only a small piece of data, we have to work with the whole object. For example, if we only need to get the firstName, lastName, and age of a user in a REST API, there‚Äôs no way we can get exactly this data without fetching the whole object.</p>

<p>There‚Äôs also a problem with under-fetching. If we want to get data from two different resources, we need to make different calls to two different endpoints. In a large application, this doesn‚Äôt scale so well since there will be cases where we only need to get a specific piece of data, not the entire object.</p>

<p>Now, imagine we‚Äôre building an application that‚Äôs going to have 100 <em>(or more)</em> endpoints. Imagine the amount of work and code that we need to write. This will become more difficult with time and the code will become hard to maintain, and document.</p>

<h2 id="versions">Versions</h2>
<p>With REST, it‚Äôs very common to see a lot of APIs with v1 or v2. In GraphQL there‚Äôs no need for it since you can evolve your APIs by adding new types or removing old ones.</p>

<p>In GraphQL, all you need to do to evolve your API is to write new code and ‚Äúdeprecate‚Äù fields which are no longer in use. You can write new types, queries, and mutations without the need to ship another version of your API.</p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>class UserType &lt; Types::BaseObject
  description "Sample user type"

  field :name, String, null: true
    deprecation_reason: "We split up the name into two"
  field :firstName, String, null: false
  field :lastName, String, null: false
end
</code></pre></div></div>

<hr />

<h2 id="graphql-enters-stage-left">GraphQL enters, stage left‚Ä¶</h2>
<p>So, back in 2012, Facebook faced a problem while they were developing their mobile apps which in-turn led to the creation of GraphQL. Those problems were common, especially when we‚Äôre talking about RESTful API design. I‚Äôve mentioned some issues already‚Ä¶</p>

<ul>
  <li>Poor performance</li>
  <li>Lots of endpoints</li>
  <li>Over or under fetching of data</li>
  <li>Shipping another version each time we need to include or remove something</li>
  <li>Difficulty understanding APIs</li>
</ul>

<p>With these concepts in mind, the devs from Facebook started work on a better way to design API‚Äôs and this then became‚Ä¶ GraphQL. While GraphQL doesn‚Äôt solve everything; it‚Äôs defiantly a much better way to consume data across a variety of platforms.</p>

<p>With GraphQL, we get a lot of new features which make building your API‚Äôs easier and allowing users of the API to get the data they need or want.</p>

<h2 id="one-endpoint-to-rule-them-all">One endpoint to rule them all!</h2>
<p>With GraphQL there‚Äôs no need to build a load of endpoints, in fact, we only get the one endpoint! And with this single endpoint, we can get as much data as we want with only a single request.</p>

<p>GraphQL wraps all of your queries, mutations, and subscriptions into a single endpoint which improves your development cycle as you don‚Äôt need to make two requests to get data from two different resources.</p>

<p>Imagine that we‚Äôre building a huge application, we won‚Äôt get a lot of endpoints and a load of code as with REST. We will get a single endpoint, and with that endpoint, we can make as many requests as we want.</p>

<p>With this ‚Äúendpoint-only‚Äù approach your API is self-documented so there‚Äôs no need for you to build documentation - GraphQL documents automatically. Developers can understand the API just by looking at the code, or by looking at a ‚Äúplayground‚Äù like GraphiQL.</p>

<h2 id="fetch-only-the-data-you-need">Fetch only the data you need</h2>
<p>No more over-fetching or under-fetching of data. With GraphQL you fetch only the data that you need. As you don‚Äôt need to call multiple endpoints to get all the data you need GraphQL improves the performance of your API, especially in case of slow network connections.</p>

<h2 id="building-consistent-apis">Building consistent API‚Äôs</h2>
<p>A lot of people think that GraphQL is pretty complicated because it involves a schema and a single endpoint. However, once you start developing API‚Äôs with it, you discover that it‚Äôs easier than you thought.</p>

<p>It makes your API more self-documented, and there‚Äôs no need for you to write a lot of documentation about it.</p>

<p>GraphQL is an agnostic query language which means you can use it with any language. At the time of writing GraphQL has support for more than <strong>18</strong> languages.</p>

